axialPractice | axialHealthcare










































































615-345-3555 





















										Practice									
Improve outcomes through improved care







Are your practitioners equipped with the insight to provide better care?
axialPractice provides practitioners with insight into their opioid patient panel and peer benchmarking. We supplement that information with educational resources and directives that enable doctors to provide the highest quality care to patients in pain.






How it works
Solutions fueled by analytics
axialPractice is a suite of tools that stratifies practitioners and patients according to risk, enabling practitioners to become educated on opioid best practices and perform their highest quality of care and prescribing.

With insight that has never before been comprehensively available, axialPractice illuminates patients’ claims experience and opioid risk factors so that practitioners are better able to create a tailored care plan that ensures better outcomes and safety for the patient.
The axialPractice toolset highlights areas which need improvement, identifies variations of practice within a network, and then educates practitioners on opioid prescribing best practices through a series of practitioner-focused resources. These tools will help reduce risk to patients and provide better outcomes through informed care.












Quality Care
Variations in practice are driving poor care
Many pain clinics do not practice evidence-based standards and therefore exhibit enormous practice variation. We developed a methodology for axialPractice, which uses 16 quality metrics that are based on the most current scientific literature and endorsed by axialHealthcare’s Scientific Advisory Board. Through axialPractice, we were able to discover the following:

Of the 100 certified pain clinics in this network, 25 are demonstrating desirable high-quality/low-cost results.
Even more pronounced than the quadrant comparison, the average cost differential between these 25 clinics and the 25 low-quality/ high-cost clinics is $7,700 per patient per year.
96% of pain patients are referred to clinics not demonstrating the desired high-quality/ low-cost results.










RIM PRACTITIONER



Creating a roadmap to identify and mitigate risks
RIM (Risk Identification and Mitigation) Practitioner reports provide monthly prescribing patterns which highlight the following for your practitioners:

How do I compare to my peers?
Am I improving?
In which areas can I improve?

The RIM Practitioner report (right) is also able to identify the following: opioid risk assessment, categories of risk, risk severity among members of the health plan, and corresponding spend increases.
We then create action points accordingly, providing practitioners with steps to reduce risk severity and prevent escalating risk.














Risk Severity
is driving higher pain spend
In order to support care coordination, RIM Practitioner report identified the following:

Developed opioid risk assessment with 7 categories of risk
Stratified members by risk severity
Identified spend increases with increasing risk severity













